fields.name: Notice Board – Cath Kidston English Rose
fields.description:
A padded notice board covered in Cath Kidston ENGLISH ROSE fabric with an ivory grosgrain ribbon.
A trellis of co-ordinating grosgrain ribbon is added and studded where the ribbons meet. The grosgrain ribbon is very sturdy and will not sag.
Finished on the back with calico and fittings ready for hanging. Finally wrapped in cellophane.
Tuck your messages, photos, shopping lists, cards, etc. behind the ribbon or pin on with map pins.
A smart and useful addition to a child’s bedroom or nursery.
SIZE IS 16″ x 19″.

fields.name: Notice Board – French City Emblem
fields.description:
A padded notice board adorned with the coat of arms of Le Puy-en-Velay on linen fabric, featuring an ivory grosgrain ribbon trellis. The coordinating grosgrain ribbon is very sturdy and will not sag, ensuring durability.
Studded at the intersections of the ribbons, the board is finished on the back with calico and comes with fittings ready for hanging. It is finally wrapped in cellophane for protection.
This elegant and practical notice board is ideal for displaying official notices, messages, photos, cards, and more. Simply tuck your items behind the ribbon or pin them on with map pins. A smart and useful addition to any municipal office or public space.
SIZE IS 16″ x 19″.

fields.name: Filing Chest/Ottoman – Ian Mankin SUFFOLK CHECK
fields.description:
This functional yet stylish piece of furniture is a fully-upholstered wooden chest that doubles as a seat or footstool when closed. When opened, it reveals a suspended filing system. The interior is lined with coordinating fabric, and the inside lid serves as a convenient notice board.
The chest stands on wooden feet or castors, making it perfect for a home office or study. It is made to order in a wide range of fabrics—fabric swatches are available upon request. You also have the option to supply your own fabric, which can reduce the cost to £195.00. The example shown features Ian Mankin SUFFOLK CHECK fabric.
